english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Two Joys
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The year after the Prince established the capital at Hanyang, he dispatched trusted ministers to govern the provinces—for he held both military and people dear. Among these were the Left Minister and the Right Minister, both sworn companions, who were sent forth with many others. They gathered to bid farewell at the southern gate of the new capital, ascending to what is called the Pavilion of Two Joys.

    Those departing pondered the unfinished work of the realm and wondered at the ambitions of their appointed tasks. Those remaining urged them onward, their solemn words heavy with care and affection. In this moment, the ache of parting mingled with the beauty of mountains and rivers, and words spilled forth unbidden. Thus they asked me to record these sentiments.

    I say: The Pavilion of Two Joys is the private retreat of the Lord of Yi-an. Upon a peak that rises solitary in the Han River's midst, a pavilion was built as a place for contemplation. The surrounding mountains stand dignified and composed, like the virtuous who guard themselves through stillness. The river flows onward unobstructed, like the wise who move without constraint. Truly this is a place where gentlemen may find joy.

    Here clouds and mists veil the distant fields, cormorants rise and fall above the sandbars, ancient trees spread their verdant shade, and cool breezes arrive of themselves. The beauty of this scene surpasses all measure. The Lord of Yi-an, kinsman of the royal house, finds refuge and delight among these mountains and waters—a man of true virtue indeed.

    Yet the ministers now face the labors of founding, with countless affairs demanding their attention. They toil and suffer, bereft of leisure for such pleasures. I recall the worthy Fan Zheng of old, who ascended the Tower of Yueyang and sighed: "To grieve for the world's sorrows before the world grieves, and to rejoice in the world's joys after the world rejoices." When I contemplate this ancient sage, his words find home in my heart.

    So do I believe: when these ministers have labored for the royal house and brought peace to the people, when their work is complete and they retire from office, then let them ascend to this pavilion with wine and staff in hand. Let them freely indulge the pleasures of their hearts and feast their eyes upon the grandeur of mountains and rivers. On that day, I shall write for them again.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Fan Zheng (范正公), also known as Fan Zhonyan, was a celebrated Song dynasty statesman and philosopher. His words about bearing the world's sorrows first and joys last became a Confucian ideal of dedicated service.
  - key: ''
    value: The Pavilion of Two Joys likely takes its name from the dual joy of both natural beauty and virtuous leisure, or from the two ministers whose departure occasioned its dedication.
  - key: ''
    value: Jeong Do-jeon (1342-1398) was a founding minister of the Joseon dynasty and a key architect of its political philosophy. This record was written during the early years of state consolidation under King Taejo.
